    <title>Questions</title>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q1">
<statement>
   Two differentiable functions
   <m>
       u
   </m>
   and
   <m>
       v
   </m>
   are graphed below near
   <m>
       x=1
   </m>
   .  Note: These graphs are symmetric about a horizontal line defined where they intersect.
  <figure xml:id="Exam2Sp26q1">
  <caption>The graphs of <m>u(x)</m> and <m>v(x)</m>.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam2Sp26q1pic" width="50%" >
<description>
</description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.1]
  % axes
  \draw[->] (-0.2,0) -- (4.5,0) node[below right] {$x$};
  \draw[->] (0,-1.2) -- (0,3.2) node[left] {$y$};
  \node[below] at (1,0){$1$};
  \draw[dashed] (1,-1.2)--(1,3.2);
  % u : increasing, positive near 1
  \draw[line width=2pt,linecolor,dashed,domain=0.2:3,samples=200] plot(\x,{0.5 + 0.8*(\x-1) + 0.2*(\x-1)^2});
  \node[linecolor] at (3.5,2.1) {$y=u(x)$};
  % v : positive but decreasing at x=1
  \draw[line width=2pt,red,domain=0.2:3,samples=200] plot(\x,{1.6 - 0.9*(\x-1) - 0.15*(\x-1)^2});
  \node[red] at (3.5,0.5) {$y=v(x)$};
  % mark x=1 points
  \fill[blue] (1,0.5) circle (3pt);
  \fill[red]  (1,1.6) circle (3pt);
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      Without formulas, determine the
      <em>
          sign
      </em>
      (positive, negative, or zero) of
      <m>
          (uv)'(1)
      </m>
      . Explain using the product rule and the picture.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Determine the
      <em>
          sign
      </em>
      of
      <m>
          \left(\dfrac{u}{v}\right)'(1)
      </m>
      . Explain using the quotient rule and the picture.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
  <li>
    <p>
      At
      <m>
          x=1
      </m>
      , the graph shows:
      <m>
          u(1) &gt; 0, u'(1) &gt; 0,
      </m>
      <m>
          v(1) &gt; 0,{\text{ and }}v'(1) = - u'(1) &lt; 0.
      </m>
      Note that
      <md>
          (uv)'(1) = u'(1)v(1)+u(1)v'(1).
      </md>
      The first term is positive (positive slope times  positive value). The second term is negative (positive  times negative). Since,
      <m>
          v'(1)=-u'(1)
      </m>
      and
      <m>
          0 &lt; u(1) &lt; v(1)
      </m>
      , the first (positive) term dominates.
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      Note that
      <md>
          \displaystyle \left( \frac{u}{v}\right)'(1) = \frac{u'(1)v(1)-u(1)v'(1)}{v(1)^{2}}.
      </md>
      The denominator is positive. In the numerator,
      <m>
          u'(1)v(1) &gt; 0
      </m>
      and
      <m>
          -u(1)v'(1)
      </m>
      is also positive since
      <m>
          v'(1)&lt;0
      </m>
      . Adding these is positive. Hence the fraction is also positive.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q2">
<statement>
        The function
        <m>
            f
        </m>
        is strictly increasing and differentiable. Its graph and a tangent line at
        <m>
            x=b
        </m>
        are shown in <xref ref="Exam2Sp26q2"/>. The slope of the tangent line is
        <m>
            \displaystyle m=\frac{3}{2}
        </m>
        . Let
        <m>
            g=f^{-1}
        </m>
        . Compute
        <m>
            g'\big(f(b)\big)
        </m>
        .
    <figure xml:id="Exam2Sp26q2">
  <caption>Graph a function <m>f(x)</m> and its tangent line at <m>x=b</m>.</caption> 
  <image xml:id="Exam2Sp26q2pic" width="50%" >
<description>
</description>
    <latex-image>
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.05]
  \draw[->] (-0.5,0)--(5.2,0) node[below right] {$x$};
  \draw[->] (0,-0.5)--(0,3.8) node[left] {$y$};
  \draw[line width=2pt,domain=0.3:4.1,samples=200] plot(\x,{0.4 + 0.6*(\x) + 0.2*(\x-2)^2});
  \node at (2.5,3.2) {$y=f(x)$};
  \draw[dashed] (2,0)--(2,3.8); \node[below] at (2,0){$b$};
  \coordinate (B) at (2,1.6);
  \fill (B) circle (3pt) node[below right] {$\,(b,f(b))$};
  % tangent through B with slope approx 0.9
  \draw[line width=1.5pt, dashed] ($(B)+(-2, -1.2)$) -- ($(B)+(2,1.2)$);
\end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<answer>
  <p>
    Slope of tangent to
    <m>
        f
    </m>
    at
    <m>
        x=b
    </m>
    is
    <m>
        m = \frac{3}{2}.
    </m>
    Since
    <m>
        g=f^{-1}
    </m>
    ,
    <md>
        \displaystyle g'(f(b)) = \frac{1}{f'(b)}= \frac{1}{3/2}= \frac{2}{3}.
    </md>
  </p>
</answer>
 </exercise>

 
<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q3">
<statement>
Let
<m>
    F(x)=\sqrt{4x^{2}+3}
</m>
. Compute
<m>
    F'(x)
</m>
and then evaluate
<m>
    F'(2)
</m>
(exact value only).
</statement>

<answer>
    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow> F'(x) \mathstrut \amp =\frac{1}{2}(4x^{2}+3)^{-1/2}\cdot 8x </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{4x}{\sqrt{4x^{2}+3}}.</mrow>
        </md>
        so that
        <md>
            <mrow> F'(2)\mathstrut \amp =\frac{8}{\sqrt{16+3}} </mrow> 
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{8}{\sqrt{19}}.</mrow>
        </md>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q4">
<statement>
A function
<m>
    f
</m>
is differentiable and satisfies
<m>
    f(3)=7
</m>
and
<m>
    f'(3)=-1.6
</m>
.
<ol marker="(a)">
    <li> <p> Find the linearization
    <m>
        L(x)
    </m>
    at
    <m>
        x=3
    </m>
    . </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Use
            <m>
                L(x)
            </m>
            to estimate
            <m>
                f(3.3)
            </m>
            .
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            If you are told
            <m>
                f''(3)&gt;0
            </m>
            , explain in one sentence whether your estimate in (b) is likely an overestimate or underestimate of
            <m>
                f(3.3)
            </m>
            .
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
 </statement>
 <answer>
    <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
                <p>
                <m>
                        L(x)=f(3)+f'(3)(x-3)=7-1.6(x-3).
                    </m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
               <m>
                        f(3.3)\approx L(3.3)=7 -1.6(0.3)=7-0.48 = 6.52.
                    </m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    If
                    <m>
                        f''(3)&gt;0
                    </m>
                    ,
                    <m>
                        f
                    </m>
                    is likely concave up near
                    <m>
                        x=3
                    </m>
                    . The tangent line then lies
                    <em>
                        below
                    </em>
                    the curve, so the linear approximation is an underestimate. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
 </answer>
 </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q5">
<statement>
Compute each derivative.
<ol marker="(a)">
    <li>
        <p>
           <m>
               h(x)= 5x^{4} - 3x + \dfrac{2}{x}
           </m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
             <m>
                 q(x)= (3x^{2}+1)\sin x
             </m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>
                r(x)= \dfrac{x^3}{2x-5}
            </m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</statement>

<answer>
    <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
                <p>
                   <m>
                       h'(x)=20x^{3} - 3 - \frac{2}{x^{2}}.
                   </m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <m>
                         q'(x)=6x\sin x + (3x^{2}+1)\cos x.
                     </m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p> Use the quotient rule:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> r'(x) \mathstrut \amp =\frac{3x^{2}(2x-5)-x^{3}(2)}{(2x-5)^{2}}</mrow> 
                        <mrow> \amp =\frac{6x^{3}-15x^{2}-2x^{3}}{(2x-5)^{2}}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp =\frac{4x^{3}-15x^{2}}{(2x-5)^{2}}.</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q6">
<statement>
The height
<m>
    H(t)
</m>
(in meters) of water in a tank is decreasing at a rate of
<m>
    0.12
</m>
m/min. The water temperature
<m>
    T
</m>
(in
<m>
    ^{\circ}
</m>
C) changes with height according to
<m>
    T(H)=18 + 0.5H.
</m>
<ol marker="(a)">
    <li> <p>Compute
    <m>
        \dfrac{dT}{dt}
    </m>
    at the instant the water is 2 m deep. </p> </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Interpret your answer with units in one sentence. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</statement>

<answer>
    <p>
        <ol marker="(a)">
            <li>
                <p> From the chain rule, 
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \frac{dT}{dt}\mathstrut \amp =\frac{dT}{dH}\frac{dH}{dt}</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp =0.5(-0.12) </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp = -0.06\ \text{°C/min}.</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The water temperature is decreasing at a rate of
                    <m>
                        0.06^{\circ}\text{C per minute}.
                    </m>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q7">
<statement>
Find the equation of the tangent line to the curve
<m>
    \displaystyle x^{2}+xy+4y^{2}=10
</m>
at the ordered pair
<m>
    (2,1)
</m>
.   
  <figure xml:id="Sp26Ex2q7pic" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A graph of <m>
    \displaystyle x^{2}+xy+4y^{2}=10
</m>.</caption>
      <image source="images/ImplicitEquationASpring26.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>The graph of a given ellipse and the ordered pair at (2,1).</description>
      </image>
</figure>
</statement>
<answer>
    <p>
        Differentiate:
        <md>
            2x + (x y' + y) + 8y y' = 0.
        </md>
        Group
        <m>
            y'
        </m>
        terms:
        <md>
            y'(x+8y)=-(2x+y),
        </md>
        <md>
            y' = \frac{-(2x+y)}{x+8y}.
        </md>
        At
        <m>
            (2,1)
        </m>
        :
        <md>
            y'=\frac{-(4+1)}{2+8}=\frac{-5}{10}=-\frac{1}{2}.
        </md>
        Tangent line:
        <md>
            y-1 = -\frac{1}{2}(x-2).
        </md>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q8">
<statement>
<p>
    You know that at <m>x=4</m>,
    <md>
        u(4)=3,\quad u'(4)=2.1,\quad v(4)=5,\quad v'(4)=-0.6.
    </md>
</p>

<p>
    Let <m>P(x)=u(x)v(x)</m> and <m>Q(x)=\dfrac{u(x)}{v(x)}</m>.
</p>
<ol marker="(a)">
<li>
    <p>
       Compute
        <m>
            P'(4)
        </m>
        .
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <p>
        Compute
        <m>
            Q'(4)
        </m>
        .
    </p>
</li>
<li>
    <p>
        Explain in one sentence whether
        <m>
            P
        </m>
        is increasing or decreasing at
        <m>
            x=4
        </m>
        .
    </p>
</li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
    <ol marker="(a)">
        <li>
            <p> We have
             <md>
                   <mrow> P'(4)\mathstrut \amp =u'(4)v(4)+u(4)v'(4) </mrow>
                   <mrow> \amp =2.1(5)+3(-0.6) </mrow> 
                   <mrow> \amp =10.5 - 1.8 </mrow>
                   <mrow> \amp = 8.7.</mrow>
               </md>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p> We have 
                <md>
                    <mrow> Q'(4) \mathstrut \amp =\frac{u'(4)v(4)-u(4)v'(4)}{v(4)^{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp =\frac{2.1(5)-3(-0.6)}{25} </mrow> 
                    <mrow> \amp =\frac{10.5+1.8}{25} </mrow> 
                    <mrow> \amp =\frac{12.3}{25} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = 0.492.</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                Since
                <m>
                    P'(4)=8.7&gt;0
                </m>
                ,
                <m>
                    P \text{ is increasing at }x=4.
                </m>
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q9">
<statement>
The graph of a periodic function
<m>
    p(x)
</m>
is shown. Which of the following is most likely to represent
<m>
    p'(x)
</m>
? [Check the appropriate box(es).]
<figure xml:id="Sp26Ex2q9pic" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <caption>A graph of <m>
    p(x)
</m> which is periodic.</caption>
      <image source="images/GraphOfNegCos2xM2.jpg" width="50%">
        <description>The graph of a periodic function.</description>
      </image>
</figure>
 <dl>
     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>\sin(2x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>-\cos(2x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>2\sin(x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>-2\cos(x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>2\sin(2x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>-2\cos(2x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>2\sin(x)-2</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>-2\cos(x)-2</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>-2\sin(x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>2\cos(x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>2\sin(\frac{1}{2}x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>

     <li>
         <title> <m>\square</m> </title>

         <p>
             <m>-2\cos(\frac{1}{2}x)</m>
         </p>
     </li>
 </dl>
</statement>
<answer>
    <p>
        <m>2\sin(2x)</m>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q10">
<statement>
<p>
    A function <m>f</m> and its derivative <m>f'</m> take the values given in <xref ref="ffprimedataExam2Sp26q10"/>.
    If <m>p(x)=f(2e^{x})</m>, compute <m>p'(0)</m>.
</p>

<table xml:id="ffprimedataExam2Sp26q10" >
        <title>Values of <m>f</m> and <m>f'</m> at various values.</title>
<tabular top="minor" left="minor">
    <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
    <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
    <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
    <col halign="center" right="minor"/>
    <row top="minor" />
    <row top="minor" bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>x</m></cell>
        <cell>0</cell>
        <cell>1</cell>
        <cell>2</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
        <cell/>
    </row>

    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>f(x)</m></cell>
        <cell>2</cell>
        <cell>1</cell>
        <cell>0</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
        <cell/>
    </row>

    <row bottom="minor">
        <cell><m>f'(x)</m></cell>
        <cell>1</cell>
        <cell>0</cell>
        <cell>2</cell>
    </row>

    <row>
        <cell/>
    </row>
</tabular>
</table>

</statement>
<answer>
    <p> Note that
        <md>
            p'(x)=f'(2e^{x})\cdot 2e^{x}.
        </md>
        At
        <m>
            x=0
        </m>
        :
        <md>
            p'(0)=f'(2e^{0})\cdot 2e^{0} = f'(2)\cdot 2.
        </md>
        From the table:
        <m>
            f'(2)=2
        </m>
        . So
        <m>
            p'(0)=4.
        </m>
    </p>
</answer>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exam2-s26-q11">
<statement>
A company sells a product at price
<m>
    p
</m>
dollars. The number of units sold
<m>
    q(p)
</m>
depends on the price. The
<alert>
    revenue
</alert>
is
<m>
    R(p) = p \cdot q(p)
</m>
. When the price is
<m>
    p = \$20
</m>
, the number of units sold is
<m>
    q(20)=600
</m>
. It is also known that
<m>
    q'(20)=-18
</m>
.
<ol marker="(a)">
    <li>
        <p>
             In this context, what does
             <m>
                 q'(20)=-18
             </m>
             mean? Use units in giving your one-sentence explanation.  
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Compute
            <m>
                R'(20)
            </m>
            .
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Interpret the meaning of the sign of
            <m>
                R'(20)
            </m>
            .
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            Assuming that the company wishes to maximize revenue, should the company raise or lower the price at
            <m>
                p=\$20
            </m>
            ? Explain briefly. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</statement>
<answer>
<ol marker="(a)">
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>
                q'(20)=-18
            </m>
            means that for each $1 increase in price at
            <m>
                p=\$20
            </m>
            , unit sales decrease by 18 units (units per dollar).
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
           <m>
                R'(p)=q(p)+p q'(p),
            </m>
            so that
            <m>
                R'(20)=600+20(-18)=600-360= 240.
            </m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
           Since
            <m>
                R'(20)&gt;0
            </m>
            , revenue is
            <em>
                increasing
            </em>
            at
            <m>
                p=20
            </m>
            . This means a small price increase will raise revenue.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
             To maximize revenue, since
             <m>
                 R'(20)&gt;0
             </m>
             , the company should raise the price (slightly). 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</answer>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>
</handout>